        "question": "Q2. ‘The Theory of the Four Humours was the main idea about the cause of disease in the Middle Ages’. How far do you agree? Explain your answer. (16 marks) You may use the following in your answer:<br>• Galen<br>• the Church<br>You must also use information of your own.",
        "starter": "The Catholic Church hindered medical progress primarily because it controlled...",
        "model": "<strong>Grade 9 Model Answer (16 marks):</strong><br><br><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1.5rem;\"><strong>To a very large extent, I agree that the Theory of the Four Humours was the main idea about the cause of disease in medieval England (c1250–c1500).</strong> While other unscientific explanations—such as divine punishment and miasma—co-existed and were widely believed, the Four Humours served as the primary, universally accepted \"rational\" framework through which medical practitioners and educated society understood, diagnosed, and physically treated sickness. </p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1.5rem;\">The primary reason for the absolute dominance of this theory was its endorsement by the ancient Roman physician Claudius <strong>Galen</strong>, whose extensive writings built directly upon the earlier work of Hippocrates. Galen argued that the human body contained four core liquids: <strong>blood, phlegm, yellow bile, and black bile</strong>, which corresponded directly to the seasons, elements, and physical qualities (hot, cold, wet, dry). Sickness was explained as a natural imbalance of these fluids—for instance, a cold was viewed as an excess of cold, wet phlegm in winter. Galen also introduced the <strong>Theory of Opposites</strong>, which taught that a humoural imbalance should be treated with its opposite quality. This practical, logical framework was highly convincing to medieval people because it matched daily bodily observations—such as sneezing excess phlegm during a cold or sweating out a hot fever.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1.5rem;\">Furthermore, the theory was maintained as the unchallenged medical standard because <strong>the Church</strong> controlled medieval education, universities, and the copying of medical manuscripts. Because Galen’s anatomical writings argued that the human body was so incredibly complex and purposeful that it must have been designed by a single \"Creator,\" his ideas aligned perfectly with Christian creation theology. <strong>Consequently</strong>, the Church strictly promoted Galen's books as absolute truth and made them the sole basis of medical training for physicians. The Church also banned human dissection and actively discouraged any independent scientific research or questioning of classical texts, viewing intellectual deviation as a sin. This institutional monopoly ensured that generations of physicians graduated from universities like Oxford and Cambridge after seven to ten years of study without ever challenging the humoural model.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1.5rem;\">However, the Theory of the Four Humours was not the sole explanation for illness at this time, as medieval society also deeply believed in <strong>supernatural causes and the theory of miasma</strong>. The Church itself taught that disease was sent directly by God as a punishment for human sin or to test a person's faith, as seen in the societal view of leprosy as a physical mark of sin. This belief led people to seek spiritual preventions and treatments, such as prayer, fasting, pilgrimages to holy shrines, and buying indulgences. Additionally, people blamed astrology, utilizing <strong>Almanacs</strong> (star charts) to determine how the alignment of planets like Mars and Saturn caused outbreaks like the Black Death in 1348. People also believed in <strong>miasma</strong>—the unscientific idea that bad, foul-smelling air rising from rotting organic matter or swamps corrupted the body's humours. </p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1.5rem;\"><strong>In conclusion, I agree to a very large extent that the Four Humours was the main idea about the cause of disease.</strong> While religious and astrological beliefs were incredibly popular, they were rarely viewed as contradictory to humoural theory. Instead, medieval people seamlessly integrated these concepts: they believed that God used the movement of the planets to create a corrupted miasma, which, once inhaled, physically upset the internal balance of the patient's humours. Because the Four Humours sat at the center of this integrated medical worldview and dictated almost all physical treatments (such as bloodletting and purging), it was undoubtedly the dominant medical idea of the Middle Ages.</p>"
