            "type": "written",
            "text": "Explain why the government's response to the Great Plague of 1665 was more effective than its response to the Black Death of 1348. (12 marks)",
            "model": "The response to the Great Plague of 1665 was far more effective because the central government and municipal authorities abandoned their traditional medieval inactivity and took **direct, highly organized administrative responsibility** to prevent the spread of disease. During the Black Death of 1348, the king's government collected no taxes for public health and possessed very little administrative power, leaving town mayors entirely unequipped to enforce quarantine or restrict travel. In contrast, in 1665, local officials strictly enforced King Charles II’s royal decree through structured, state-funded containment schemes. **This led directly to the Lord Mayor of London** and local aldermen taking charge of the city's defenses, dividing London into distinct wards, and hiring poor citizens to serve as specialized municipal officers. These included **searchers** to systematically examine corpses to track hot spots, and **wardens** to manage sanitation, demonstrating a level of structured disease prevention that did not exist in 1348.<br><br>This administrative progress was most clearly seen in the enforcement of **strict, compulsory quarantine policies**. Under the Mayor’s orders, if a single member of a household caught the plague, the entire family was subjected to a compulsory **28-day quarantine** inside their home. To enforce this, the city hired specialized **watchmen** who stood guard outside the boarded-up doors of infected houses to prevent anyone from entering or leaving. The front door was painted with a red cross and the words \"Lord have mercy on us\" to warn the public. **This meant that** the government physically broke the chain of transmission, keeping infected individuals off the streets and protecting the wider public from immediate contagion. This organized containment was a massive improvement over 1348, when infected individuals mixed freely with the healthy, rapidly accelerating the spread of the disease.<br><br>Furthermore, the response in 1665 was enhanced by **the systematic collection and analysis of statistical data**. Following the Renaissance rise of empirical science, London authorities began printing weekly **Bills of Mortality**, which listed the exact numbers and causes of deaths in each parish. **Consequently**, the Mayor and aldermen could identify which neighborhoods were experiencing plague spikes and implement targeted quarantines, clear rubbish, or order the slaughter of **cats and dogs** (while slaughtering predators was biologically counterproductive as it increased the rat population, it demonstrated an unprecedented willingness to intervene systematically). **As a result**, the government shifted from the purely spiritual, uncoordinated reactions of 1348 to a proactive, data-driven public health strategy that successfully limited the epidemic's geographic spread."
