        "model": "<strong>Grade 9 Model Answer (16 marks):</strong><br><br><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1.5rem;\"><strong>To a very large extent, I agree that the discovery of the structure of DNA was the most significant breakthrough in understanding the causes of illness in the modern period.</strong> For centuries, medical understanding was restricted to external pathogens or physical trauma. By decoding the human genetic blueprint, the discovery of DNA unlocked a completely new genetic paradigm of medicine, allowing doctors to explain, predict, and target non-communicable, hereditary illnesses. While the identification of lifestyle factors has had a massive practical impact on public health legislation, DNA represents the ultimate scientific frontier of modern medical science.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1.5rem;\">On the one hand, the mapping of DNA fundamentally transformed medical understanding by proving that many chronic diseases are caused by internal, inherited genetic instructions. In 1953, James <strong>Watson and Crick</strong> successfully mapped the double-helix structure of DNA, relying heavily on the uncredited X-ray crystallography photographs produced by Rosalind Franklin. This molecular breakthrough allowed scientists to look inside the human cell and was scaled up globally through the <strong>Human Genome Project</strong> (launched in 1990 and completed in 2003). By mapping all three billion chemical base pairs, scientists identified the specific mutated or faulty genes responsible for hereditary illnesses like cystic fibrosis, Down's syndrome, and haemophilia. Today, this allows for predictive genetic testing—for instance, individuals can screen for mutated BRCA1/2 genes to assess their hereditary risk of developing breast cancer long before any physical symptoms manifest.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1.5rem;\">On the other hand, it can be argued that the identification of <strong>lifestyle factors</strong> has been a more significant breakthrough for the health of the general population. While genetic disorders affect a minority, chronic lifestyle-related illnesses are the leading causes of death in modern Britain. Throughout the twentieth century, epidemiological research proved how personal choices regarding tobacco, diet, alcohol, and exercise cause disease. Most notably, a landmark <strong>1950 study by the British Medical Research Council</strong> provided indisputable statistical proof linking smoking directly to lung cancer. This understanding of \"nurture\" over \"nature\" led to highly effective government prevention legislation—including raising the legal tobacco buying age to 18, banning cigarette advertising, and implementing the compulsory <strong>2007 ban on smoking in enclosed public workplaces</strong>.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1.5rem;\">Furthermore, the clinical application of both genetic and lifestyle discoveries was entirely dependent on <strong>advances in modern diagnostic technologies</strong>. In 1900, diagnosis was still highly subjective, based on examining a patient’s physical symptoms. Throughout the twentieth century, this was revolutionized by high-tech diagnostic testing: <strong>blood tests</strong> (from the 1930s) allowed for the non-invasive screening of internal conditions; <strong>X-rays</strong> (from 1895) revealed internal structures; and <strong>CT and MRI scans</strong> constructed detailed, 3D images to locate deep brain tumors and lung cancers when they were the size of a pea. Paired with cellular <strong>biopsies</strong> and electrocardiograms (ECGs), these technologies allowed doctors to pinpoint physical and chemical causes of illness with unprecedented, scientific accuracy.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1.5rem;\"><strong>In conclusion, I agree to a very large extent that the discovery of DNA was the most significant breakthrough.</strong> While the identification of <strong>lifestyle factors</strong> led to immediate public health campaigns like <strong>Change4Life</strong> that saved millions of lives, and while modern diagnostic machines were essential for clinical testing, these developments represented the perfection of existing nineteenth-century observational science. In contrast, the discovery of DNA by <strong>Watson and Crick</strong> represented an entirely new scientific paradigm. By allowing doctors to actively read and eventually edit the human biological code, DNA permanently altered the future direction of global medicine, shifting the ultimate goal of science from treating symptoms to correcting our genetic blueprint.</p>"
