            "type": "written",
            "text": "Explain why there was rapid progress in the development of penicillin in the 1940s. (12 marks)",
            "model": "The rapid progress in the development of penicillin during the 1940s was driven primarily by the systematic scientific work of **Howard Florey and Ernst Chain** at Oxford University, who turned an abandoned laboratory curiosity into a stable, usable drug. Although Alexander Fleming discovered the antibacterial properties of the mold by accident in 1928, he lacked the chemical expertise to purify it and abandoned his research in 1931, believing it was too unstable to be used as anything more than a minor local antiseptic. In 1938–1939, Florey (an Australian pathologist) and Chain (a German biochemist) revived Fleming's research. Chain successfully solved the chemical purification challenges, and in **1940**, they proved penicillin's life-saving effectiveness on infected mice, followed by their first human trial on Albert Alexander in **1941**. **Consequently**, their rigorous clinical research proved that penicillin was a highly effective, non-toxic antibiotic capable of destroying fatal blood infections inside the human bloodstream, providing the essential scientific justification for mass production.<br><br>This scientific success was turned into a global pharmaceutical industry through massive **government funding and intervention** under the urgent pressures of the **Second World War**. Despite Florey and Chain's success, British chemical companies were fully occupied with the war effort and could not provide assistance. In July 1941, Florey traveled to the USA to secure funding, arriving just as the American government realized the drug's immense military value for treating infected battlefield wounds and preventing fatal gas gangrene. **Consequently**, the US Government intervened on an unprecedented scale, providing massive federal grants to Florey's team and funding American pharmaceutical companies to purchase expensive industrial equipment, including **giant deep-fermentation tanks**. **This wartime mobilization led directly to** a manufacturing revolution, scaling up production from virtually nothing to over **2.3 million doses** in time to treat Allied casualties on D-Day in June 1944.<br><br>Furthermore, this rapid development was accelerated by **unprecedented international scientific collaboration and agricultural technology**. To maximize the yield of penicillin, researchers at a government-backed laboratory in Peoria, Illinois, systematically searched for more productive strains of the mold, discovering a highly potent strain on a cantaloupe melon in 1943. **This meant that** scientists could combine the new high-yield strain with the industrial deep-fermentation technology, multiplying the production rate of pure penicillin millions of times over. This integration of microbiology, chemical engineering, and state planning permanently established penicillin as the world's first mass-produced antibiotic. **As a result**, bacterial infections—which had previously been the leading cause of death after surgery or minor injuries—became completely curable, permanently transforming modern global healthcare."
