            "model": "A major reason why the British government took a highly active, compulsory role in preventing disease after 1900 was the **astronomical rise in the cost of running the National Health Service (NHS)**, which made preventative medicine far more cost-effective than clinical treatment. When the NHS was launched in 1948, it committed the state to providing free healthcare from \"the cradle to the grave\". As high-tech diagnostic scans, specialized drug therapies, and complex surgical operations became incredibly expensive in the late twentieth century, treating chronic, non-communicable lifestyle illnesses placed an unsustainable financial burden on taxpayers. **Consequently**, the government abandoned any remaining laissez-faire attitudes and realized that actively preventing disease was a financial necessity to safeguard the state’s resources. **This led directly to** the launch of aggressive, state-funded **lifestyle campaigns**—such as the digital **Change4Life** campaign to combat obesity and Type 2 diabetes—alongside highly coercive, compulsory legislation like sugar taxes to prevent chronic diseases before they required expensive hospital care.<br><br>This fiscal motivation was supported by the launch of **targeted public health and lifestyle campaigns** designed to force behavioral changes across the population. Throughout the twentieth century, epidemiological research proved how personal choices regarding tobacco, alcohol, and diet directly caused major killer diseases like lung cancer and cardiovascular disease. **Consequently**, the government abandoned its traditional role as a simple provider of clean water and began actively regulating the personal behaviors of its citizens. The state launched aggressive public education campaigns, printed graphic health warnings on cigarette boxes, and passed the compulsory **2007 ban on smoking in enclosed public workplaces**. By using its legislative power to discourage smoking and unhealthy diets, the government sought to actively prevent chronic disease, demonstrating a highly interventionist and protective approach to public health.<br><br>Furthermore, this active government role was driven by **increased political democracy and shifting social expectations** regarding the welfare state. By the early twentieth century, successive Reform Acts had granted the vote to the entire adult working-class population. **This meant that** to win elections, political parties had to directly address the health, welfare, and social security of the masses. This political shift was heavily accelerated by the publication of the **1942 Beveridge Report**, which identified \"Disease\" as one of the five giant evils in society and recommended that the government take charge of public welfare. **Consequently**, the public expected the state to play a proactive role in keeping the nation healthy. **As a result**, the government was given a clear democratic mandate to introduce highly interventionist, compulsory preventative measures—such as making the smallpox vaccine compulsory, launching national immunisation programs, and funding public health education—to protect the voters who kept them in power."
