          "model_answer": "<p style=\"margin-bottom: 1.5rem;\">During the twentieth and twenty-first centuries, the British government underwent a massive ideological transformation, abandoning its traditional \"laissez-faire\" attitude to take direct, legally compulsory responsibility for the health of its citizens. This shift occurred because of a combination of powerful factors: the soaring financial burden of chronic illnesses on the newly created <strong>National Health Service (NHS)</strong>, the sheer scale of modern epidemics like <strong>lung cancer</strong> which made hands-off policies politically and socially impossible, and the development of undeniable scientific proof that targeted state intervention would actively save lives.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1.5rem;\">The primary reason why the government took action was the rise of the devastating <strong>lung cancer</strong> epidemic, which quickly became too large to ignore. Following aggressive advertising campaigns by tobacco companies after the First World War, cigarette smoking soared in popularity. By the 1950s, doctors noticed a catastrophic rise in lung cancer deaths, and in <strong>1950</strong>, the British Medical Research Council published a study proving conclusively that smoking was the direct cause of this fatal disease. Initially, the government was highly reluctant to act because they earned around <strong>£4 billion a year from tobacco tax</strong> and feared restricting personal freedom. However, as lung cancer became the second most common cancer in the UK, killing tens of thousands of citizens annually, the government was forced to intervene. They launched aggressive campaigns to encourage current smokers to quit (Stoptober), protect non-smokers from second-hand smoke (the 2007 enclosed public smoking ban), and prevent youth uptake (raising the buying age to 18 in 2007 and banning television advertising).</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1.5rem;\">This intervention was heavily accelerated by the economic reality of funding the <strong>National Health Service (NHS)</strong>. Launched in <strong>1948</strong> by Health Minister Aneurin Bevan, the NHS revolutionized medicine by making comprehensive medical treatment entirely free at the point of use. When the NHS was created, its main focus was on *treating* people who were already sick. However, as the decades passed, the cost of high-tech clinical treatments—including chemotherapy, radiotherapy, and complex lung surgeries—skyrocketed, placing a severe financial strain on the taxpayer-funded system. By 1985, treating smoking-related illnesses was costing the NHS a staggering <strong>£165 million a year</strong>. The government quickly realized that the NHS would become financially unsustainable if it only treated chronic diseases. Therefore, they took aggressive action to improve public health because <strong>prevention was far cheaper than clinical cure</strong>, shifting the primary focus of the NHS toward proactive health campaigns and preventative medicine.</p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 1.5rem;\">Finally, the government took action because advanced scientific and epidemiological discoveries provided the precise evidence required to justify state intervention. In the nineteenth century, the government was slow to act on public health because they did not understand how disease spread. For example, when John Snow proved cholera was water-borne in 1854, the government took twenty years to build sewers because they lacked a scientific explanation. In the modern era, however, Pasteur's Germ Theory, the mapping of DNA, and precise lifestyle studies provided <strong>undeniable scientific proof</strong> of disease causes. Once researchers proved that second-hand smoke caused fatal lung cancer in non-smokers, the government had the scientific and ethical backing to ban indoor smoking. Because the government understood exactly *how* disease was spread and *why* people fell ill, they recognized that their interventions would have a guaranteed, positive impact on the health of the nation, prompting them to pass compulsory legislation.</p>",
          "model": "The British government took decisive action to improve public health in the modern era because of the lessons of military physical decline during the **Boer War (1899–1902)**, which proved that the state's geopolitical power depended on the health of its working-class population. During enlistment, the government was horrified to discover that up to **40% of working-class recruits were physically unfit for military service** due to childhood malnutrition, rickets, and poor sanitation in industrial slums. **This national security crisis served as a powerful wake-up call**, proving that the traditional \"laissez-faire\" policy was actively undermining Britain’s military and economic strength. **Consequently**, the government took immediate legislative action, passing the **1906 Education (Provision of Meals) Act** to provide free school meals for needy children and the **1911 National Insurance Act** to give workers access to GPs and health insurance. **As a result**, the state recognized that public health was a core national security asset, driving the creation of the modern welfare state.<br><br>This national security motivation was further reinforced by the need to protect citizens from **severe environmental disasters** caused by industrial pollution. In December 1952, London was engulfed by the **Great Smog**, a lethal combination of cold weather, windless conditions, and toxic sulfur dioxide coal smoke that reduced visibility and killed an estimated 4,000 to 12,000 citizens from respiratory failure in just a few weeks. **This environmental crisis forced the government to act**, resulting in the **Clean Air Acts of 1956 and 1968** which legally banned the burning of coal in designated urban \"smoke control areas\" and mandated that factories transition to cleaner fuels. **Consequently**, the state used its legal authority to directly regulate the air quality of British cities, demonstrating that the government was willing to override industrial interests to prevent chronic respiratory illnesses and protect public health.<br><br>Furthermore, the government took action because of the **epidemic of lung cancer**, which became the leading cause of cancer deaths in Britain by the mid-twentieth century. Following a landmark **1950 study by the Medical Research Council** which proved the direct link between tobacco smoke and lung cancer, the government recognized that lifestyle choices had become the biggest killers of modern citizens. **Consequently**, the state took aggressive legislative action, progressively banning TV cigarette adverts in 1965, outlawing all tobacco advertising in 2005, and enforcing the **2007 ban on smoking in enclosed public workplaces** to protect citizens from secondhand smoke. **This meant that** the government completely abandoned its traditional hands-off approach and adopted a highly regulatory, protective \"nanny state\" model to actively prevent chronic, lifestyle-related fatalities, representing a complete transformation of public health policy."
