          "text": "**Blood Transfusions and Storage Problems**\n\nJames Blundell carried out the first human-to-human blood transfusions in 1818 to save women suffering from blood loss during childbirth. However, early transfusions were highly dangerous because blood types were not understood, often resulting in rejection and death.\n\nIn 1901, the Austrian doctor Karl Landsteiner revolutionised the process by discovering three blood groups (A, B, and O), with a fourth (AB) found a year later. In 1907, blood group O was identified as the universal blood group.\n\nDespite this, a massive problem remained: blood coagulated (clotted) as soon as it left the body, meaning it could not be stored. Because blood could not be stored in a bank, transfusions had to be carried out with the donor and the patient connected directly to each other by a tube in the exact same room. This made dealing with mass casualties on a battlefield virtually impossible.",
