      "vocab_cloze_text": "The daily reality of life in the British sector of the Western Front presented medical officers with challenges that had never been seen in civilian practice. Soldiers standing for days in deep, waterlogged mud frequently developed [Trench Foot], which could easily turn gangrenous if they did not change their socks and apply whale oil. In the crowded, unhygienic conditions of the dugouts, body lice thrived in the seams of uniforms, transmitting [Trench Fever] and causing high fevers across entire battalions. Beyond these physical illnesses, the relentless noise and violence of heavy artillery shellfire led to thousands of cases of [Shell Shock], forcing the army to develop new ways of diagnosing and treating psychological trauma close to the front line.",
