          "answer": "<table style=\"width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-bottom: 20px;\"><tbody><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; font-weight: bold; background-color: #f9fafb; width: 40%;\">Detail in Source A that I would follow up:</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;\">\"The surgeons are constantly amputating limbs to stop the spread of gangrene...\"</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; font-weight: bold; background-color: #f9fafb;\">Question I would ask:</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;\">What percentage of wounded soldiers who underwent amputations at Casualty Clearing Stations survived their injuries compared to those treated with wound excision (debridement) or the Carrel-Dakin method?</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; font-weight: bold; background-color: #f9fafb;\">What type of source I could use:</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;\">Official RAMC Medical Records (specifically the admission and discharge registers or surgical logs of a specific Casualty Clearing Station from 1916).</td></tr><tr><td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px; font-weight: bold; background-color: #f9fafb;\">How this might help answer my question:</td><td style=\"border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 12px;\">These records would provide statistical data on the exact surgical treatments performed, showing how many patients underwent amputation versus conservative wound treatment, and recording whether they survived or died, allowing me to measure the clinical effectiveness of the medical staff's decisions.</td></tr></tbody></table>"
